<HEADLINE>
MOST RESPONDENTS DISSATISFIED WITH DPP'S PERFORMANCE: SURVEY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 26 (CNA) 05/26/07  15:43:47 (By Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
The majority of respondents to a recent survey have expressed
disapproval over the performance of the ruling Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP), pollsters said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by National Taiwan Normal University and
ChinaTimes.com via telephone among 1,070 people between April 30
and May 3. It had a margin of error of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey results, 68 percent of the respondents
are dissatisfied with the DPP's performance over the past seven
years since it won the presidency in 2000, with the party's
efforts to improve the economy receiving the most complaints.
</P>
<P>
Among the 32 percent of respondents who expressed satisfaction
with the DPP's performance, they are most happy with the DPP's
efforts to promote a name-change campaign and a new constitution.
</P>
<P>
Asked to rate the performance of President Chen Shui-bian on a
10-point scale, 23 percent of the respondents gave him five
points and 22.5 percent gave him zero. Only 28 percent gave him
more than six points.
</P>
<P>
While 74.4 percent of respondents said they will go to the polls
for the March 2008 presidential election, 41.8 percent indicated
their intention to vote for opposition Kuomintang  nominee Ma
Ying-jeou, compared with 11.7 percent who planned to vote for DPP
nominee Frank Hsieh.
</P>
<P>
On what makes a good president, 69.8 percent of the respondents
mentioned the ability to govern the country, 23.3 percent named
integrity and 1.8 percent mentioned language ability.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 32 percent of respondents identified the media as the
"largest source of chaos" in the country over the past seven
years.
</P>
<P>
While 24 percent of respondents said Chen is responsible for the
chaotic situation,  21.8 percent said the Legislative Yuan is
responsible, according to the survey.
</P>
